\title{Linear}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Manage issues, projects & team workflows in Linear. Use when the user wants to read, create or updates tickets in Linear.}

\subtree{
\title{Linear}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{This skill provides a structured workflow for managing issues, projects & team workflows in Linear. It ensures consistent integration with the Linear MCP server, which offers natural-language project management for issues, projects, documentation, and team collaboration.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Linear MCP server must be connected and accessible via OAuth}
\li{Confirm access to the relevant Linear workspace, teams, and projects}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Required Workflow}
\p{\strong{Follow these steps in order. Do not skip steps.}}

\subtree{
\title{Step 0: Set up Linear MCP (if not already configured)}
\p{If any MCP call fails because Linear MCP is not connected, pause and set it up:}

\ol{
\li{Add the Linear MCP:}
\li{\code{\startverb codex mcp add linear --url https://mcp.linear.app/mcp\stopverb}}
\li{Enable remote MCP client:}
\li{Set \code{\startverb [features] rmcp_client = true\stopverb} in \code{\startverb config.toml\stopverb} \strong{or} run \code{\startverb codex --enable rmcp_client\stopverb}}
\li{Log in with OAuth:}
\li{\code{\startverb codex mcp login linear\stopverb}}
}

\p{After successful login, the user will have to restart codex. You should finish your answer and tell them so when they try again they can continue with Step 1.}

\p{\strong{Windows/WSL note:} If you see connection errors on Windows, try configuring the Linear MCP to run via WSL:}

\pre{\startverb
{"mcpServers": {"linear": {"command": "wsl", "args": ["npx", "-y", "mcp-remote", "https://mcp.linear.app/sse", "--transport", "sse-only"]}}}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 1}
\p{Clarify the user's goal and scope (e.g., issue triage, sprint planning, documentation audit, workload balance). Confirm team/project, priority, labels, cycle, and due dates as needed.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2}
\p{Select the appropriate workflow (see Practical Workflows below) and identify the Linear MCP tools you will need. Confirm required identifiers (issue ID, project ID, team key) before calling tools.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3}
\p{Execute Linear MCP tool calls in logical batches:}

\ul{
\li{Read first (list/get/search) to build context.}
\li{Create or update next (issues, projects, labels, comments) with all required fields.}
\li{For bulk operations, explain the grouping logic before applying changes.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4}
\p{Summarize results, call out remaining gaps or blockers, and propose next actions (additional issues, label changes, assignments, or follow-up comments).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Available Tools}
\p{Issue Management: \code{\startverb list_issues\stopverb}, \code{\startverb get_issue\stopverb}, \code{\startverb create_issue\stopverb}, \code{\startverb update_issue\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_my_issues\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_issue_statuses\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_issue_labels\stopverb}, \code{\startverb create_issue_label\stopverb}}

\p{Project & Team: \code{\startverb list_projects\stopverb}, \code{\startverb get_project\stopverb}, \code{\startverb create_project\stopverb}, \code{\startverb update_project\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_teams\stopverb}, \code{\startverb get_team\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_users\stopverb}}

\p{Documentation & Collaboration: \code{\startverb list_documents\stopverb}, \code{\startverb get_document\stopverb}, \code{\startverb search_documentation\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_comments\stopverb}, \code{\startverb create_comment\stopverb}, \code{\startverb list_cycles\stopverb}}
}

\subtree{
\title{Practical Workflows}
\ul{
\li{Sprint Planning: Review open issues for a target team, pick top items by priority, and create a new cycle (e.g., "Q1 Performance Sprint") with assignments.}
\li{Bug Triage: List critical/high-priority bugs, rank by user impact, and move the top items to "In Progress."}
\li{Documentation Audit: Search documentation (e.g., API auth), then open labeled "documentation" issues for gaps or outdated sections with detailed fixes.}
\li{Team Workload Balance: Group active issues by assignee, flag anyone with high load, and suggest or apply redistributions.}
\li{Release Planning: Create a project (e.g., "v2.0 Release") with milestones (feature freeze, beta, docs, launch) and generate issues with estimates.}
\li{Cross-Project Dependencies: Find all "blocked" issues, identify blockers, and create linked issues if missing.}
\li{Automated Status Updates: Find your issues with stale updates and add status comments based on current state/blockers.}
\li{Smart Labeling: Analyze unlabeled issues, suggest/apply labels, and create missing label categories.}
\li{Sprint Retrospectives: Generate a report for the last completed cycle, note completed vs. pushed work, and open discussion issues for patterns.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tips for Maximum Productivity}
\ul{
\li{Batch operations for related changes; consider smart templates for recurring issue structures.}
\li{Use natural queries when possible ("Show me what John is working on this week").}
\li{Leverage context: reference prior issues in new requests.}
\li{Break large updates into smaller batches to avoid rate limits; cache or reuse filters when listing frequently.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\ul{
\li{Authentication: Clear browser cookies, re-run OAuth, verify workspace permissions, ensure API access is enabled.}
\li{Tool Calling Errors: Confirm the model supports multiple tool calls, provide all required fields, and split complex requests.}
\li{Missing Data: Refresh token, verify workspace access, check for archived projects, and confirm correct team selection.}
\li{Performance: Remember Linear API rate limits; batch bulk operations, use specific filters, or cache frequent queries.}
}
}
}